":"1293","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1200–1278":"1200–1278","1203–1293":"1203–1293","1225–1293":"1225–1293","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1175–Female":"1175–Deceased","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1293":"1293","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bussey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk, of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy, France: Boucé in Orne, from which came Robert de Buci mentioned in Domesday Book, Bouce (Manche), or Bucy-le-Long (Aisne). All are named with a Latin personal name <i>Buccius</i> (presumably a derivative of <i>bucca</i> ‘mouth’) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","English: variant of   Boosey  .","Americanized form of German   Busse  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessey","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): perhaps a variant of   Bussey  .","French: habitational name from any of the places in Côte-d'Or and Loire named Bessey, from the Gallo-Roman estate <i>Bassiacum</i>, from the Roman personal name <i>Bassius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."]},{"name":"Boosey","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>bosy</i> ‘ox-stall, cow-stall’ (Old English <i>bōsig</i>)."]},{"name":"Bussie","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bussey  , of Norman origin. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bucey","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Bussey  ."]},{"name":"Busey","meanings":["English: variant of   Bussey  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Hugh Bussey was born in 1200, in England, United Kingdom, his father, William D Bussey, was 25 and his mother, Rose or Roesia Fitz baldwin de Clare, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Dive. He died in 1278, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1200–1278":"1200–1278","1203–1293":"1203–1293","1225–1293":"1225–1293","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1293":"1293","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1200–1278":"1200–1278","1203–1293":"1203–1293","1225–1293":"1225–1293","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1293":"1293","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1200–1278":"1200–1278","1203–1293":"1203–1293","1225–1293":"1225–1293","1175–Male":"1175–Décédé","1175–Female":"1175–Décédée","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","1293":"1293","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sir Hugh Bussey est né en 1200, à Angleterre, Royaum